The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Sunday, July 25, 2004 				 Centre call for power to panchayats
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, July 24: The Centre today called for effective devolution of power in rural areas through panchayats after forming a separate panchayati raj ministry for the first time.																								The doctrines of poverty alleviation and rural prosperity are only possible through the institutional mechanism of panchayati raj, Mani Shankar Aiyar, the Union panchayati raj minister said here today at the inaugural of a two-day round table on panchayati raj.																								On the Block-Level Pre-litigation Conciliation Board Bill, Aiyar said: The bill, in my opinion, does not infringe on the constitutional provision related to panchayati raj.																								Over two dozen panchayat ministers and senior officials from 20 states across the country attended the round-table inaugurated by Bengal chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee.																								Todays meeting was the first of seven round-tables to be organised in states till December on the plan to be taken up by the Centre and states for devolution of functions and finances and empowerment of gram sabhas.CM vow to students																								The state government will help students take interest in technical education and develop a career out of it, Bhattacharjee said at the golden jubilee celebrations of the Ramakrishna Mission Shilpamandir at Belur.																								Lakhs of students pass Madhyamik and higher secondary each year and all of them dont get first class. What they will do is not just their responsibility but also the governments, the chief minister said. 
